Lebanon's Comprehensive Crisis
Beirut — In retrospect, financial crises usually seem to have warning signs before they occur; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of historical events.
The situation in Lebanon is similar now, as a foreseeable crisis has plunged the country into a state of high instability.
Since the end of Lebanon's prolonged civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been sustained by external borrowing, inevitably leading to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, the inflow of foreign capital had to come to a halt. This turning point arrived toward the end of 2019, when a series of negative shocks followed one after another.
The "sudden stop" of this capital has brought about a severe triple crisis to the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current account deficit has reached as high as 25 percent of its gross domestic product, with its export base too small to cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is financial.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of the economic downturn, with budget deficits already substantial—reaching 10% of GDP in 2019—and continuing to expand rapidly.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, which were the primary recipients of foreign capital inflows, have heavily invested in Lebanon's sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises collectively pushed Lebanon's economy into a deep abyss.
Companies eager for loans and imports have started laying off workers or shutting down completely.
An economic recession could lead to a Great Depression in Lebanon.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic system is not oil, but remittances from overseas workers, who are attracted by high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the US dollar.
It's therefore no surprise that signs of "Dutch disease" are everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national saving rate to an implausibly low level — just 3% of GDP.
The level of inequality is very high and is still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, significantly weakening tradable industries.
Lebanon has been losing its educated youth due to a lack of exportable goods and services.
But more importantly, the large-scale inflow of capital allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have siphoned wealth from both the public and private sectors to establish a bloated patronage ruling clique.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even the power supply is discontinuous and unreliable, while the broader challenges facing the macroeconomy remain completely unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has overwhelmingly favored the elite in its response to Lebanon's economic crisis, indicating that the crisis may eventually be "resolved" with the support of the poor and the middle class, further consolidating sectarian politics.
For example, the country refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank—including politicians in power—to decide how much cash could be withdrawn.
In fact, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad while ordinary citizens struggle to access their savings.
In addition, the central bank has lowered deposit rates but has not yet reduced interest rates on public debt, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its external debt, primarily owed to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may begin selling state-owned assets to elite-connected entities at fire-sale prices.
At the same time, the official exchange rate remained unchanged, while elites were allowed access to U.S. dollars at the lower rate, whereas ordinary citizens faced the reality of the rapidly declining free market exchange rate. Currently, the free market exchange rate is discounted by 40%.
When the country starts printing liras to pay public servants' salaries, the depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits (which account for more than 80% of all deposits) in lira, thereby creating conditions to eliminate public debt through inflation.
As the cost of debt reduction through the "liraization" of deposits is shifted onto depositors, the banks' equity is basically spared.
If this scenario becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The emigration of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant community — upon which this system depends — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system that can be increasingly controlled by cheaper shelters.
In the end, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to that of Venezuela.
By contrast, the establishment of the new republic promoted by the revolutionaries would take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance falls far short of its potential, and that performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and create greater synergies with the immigrant community.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement aims to pursue an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital, and to forcibly reduce deposits of savers holding more than 1% of total deposits.
They support moderate currency depreciation and a thorough improvement in the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corruption and increasing spending on social programs and infrastructure.
The inevitable recession will be mitigated with the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a broader struggle emerging as the country seeks new political solutions.
The financial crisis posed a fatal threat to the country; yet it also represented an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
